\figureSyntax

\section{Judgements}
The basic judgements are about what can happen when a Verse expression is evaluated.
The outcomes we have judgements for are:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textit{succeeds}, meaning that the evaluation of the expression will produce exactly one result.
\item \textit{fails}, meaning that the evaluation of the expression will produce no results.
\item \textit{decides}, meaning that the evaluation of the expression will, at runtime, produce zero or one result.
\item \textit{well-formed}, meaning that the expressions is syntactically well-formed and has no unbound variables.
  The other judgements simply assume that the expressions are well-formed.
\end{itemize}
The judgements are always relative to some assumptions, written $\Gamma$.
The three judgements are written \jsucceeds{\Gamma}{|e|}, \jfails{\Gamma}{|e|}, and \jdecides{\Gamma}{|e|}.

The goal of the verifier is to verify that for a program |p| we can deduce \jwellformed{\noassump}{|p|} and \jsucceeds{\noassump}{|p|}.

\subsection{Assumptions}
The assumptions are of the forms \asucceeds{|a|}, \afails{|a|}, \adecides{|a|}, and \aexists{|x|}.
The assumptions are ordered and later assumptions may depend on earlier ones.

Formally,
$$
\begin{array}{rcl}
  A & ::= & \asucceeds{|a|} \vb \afails{|a|} \vb \adecides{|a|} \vb \aexists{|x|} \\
  |a| & ::= & |x == v| \vb |x == apply1 f y| \\
  \Gamma & ::= & \noassump \vb \Gamma, A \\
\end{array}
$$

Some examples
\begin{itemize}
\item \asucceeds{|x == 5|} means that we know for certain that |x| is 5.
\item \afails{|x == 5|} means that we know for certain that |x| is not 5.
\item \adecides{|x == 5|} means that we do not know statically if |x| is 5, but we can decide at runtime.
\end{itemize}

